   "source": [
    "This machine learning project is designed to help East Village Productions classify their new songs into different genres in the best way possible. The project aims to identify the most important features of songs that can help with genre classification, and also provide insights into which features should be targeted to maximize profits.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset used for this machine learning project is a Spotify dataset obtained from Kaggle, which contains 232,725 rows and 17 columns. The columns in the dataset are as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "acousticness(float number):\n",
    "A confidence measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic. 1.0 represents high confidence the track is acoustic.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "danceability(float number): \n",
    "Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "duration_ms(integer): \n",
    "The duration of the track in milliseconds.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "energy(float number): \n",
    "Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude scores low on the scale. Perceptual features contributing to this attribute include dynamic range, perceived loudness, timbre, onset rate, and general entropy.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "id(string):\n",
    "The Spotify ID for the track.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "instrumentalness(float number): \n",
    "Predicts whether a track contains no vocals. \"Ooh\" and \"aah\" sounds are treated as instrumental in this context. Rap or spoken word tracks are clearly \"vocal\". The closer the instrumentalness value is to 1.0, the greater likelihood the track contains no vocal content. Values above 0.5 are intended to represent instrumental tracks, but confidence is higher as the value approaches 1.0.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "key(integer): \n",
    "The key the track is in. Integers map to pitches using standard Pitch Class notation. E.g. 0 = C, 1 = C♯/D♭, 2 = D, and so on. If no key was detected, the value is -1.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "liveness(float number): \n",
    "Detects the presence of an audience in the recording. Higher liveness values represent an increased probability that the track was performed live. A value above 0.8 provides strong likelihood that the track is live.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "loudness(float number): \n",
    "The overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB). Loudness values are averaged across the entire track and are useful for comparing relative loudness of tracks. Loudness is the quality of a sound that is the primary psychological correlate of physical strength (amplitude). Values typically range between -60 and 0 db.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "mode(integer):\n",
    "Mode indicates the modality (major or minor) of a track, the type of scale from which its melodic content is derived. Major is represented by 1 and minor is 0.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "speechiness(float number): \n",
    "Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track. The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g. talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value. Values above 0.66 describe tracks that are probably made entirely of spoken words. Values between 0.33 and 0.66 describe tracks that may contain both music and speech, either in sections or layered, including such cases as rap music. Values below 0.33 most likely represent music and other non-speech-like tracks.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "tempo(float number): \n",
    "The overall estimated tempo of a track in beats per minute (BPM). In musical terminology, tempo is the speed or pace of a given piece and derives directly from the average beat duration.\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "time_signature(integer):\n",
    "An estimated time signature. The time signature (meter) is a notational convention to specify how many beats are in each bar (or measure). The time signature ranges from 3 to 7 indicating time signatures of \"3/4\", to \"7/4\".\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "valence(float number): \n",
    "A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry).\n",
    "\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "This dataset can be used to train a machine learning model to predict the genre of a song based on its features. The features in the dataset can also be analyzed to identify the most important ones for genre classification and for maximizing profits for East Village Productions.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Project steps\n",
    "The data modeling process involved an exploratory data analysis phase, followed by the creation of baseline models and more advanced models using pipelines and grid searches. The performance of these models was evaluated on a hold-out test set, and the best-performing model was identified for genre classification. Metric for this project is accuracy score."
   ]

    "## Running the base models"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "48ded58b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##### Train test split\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "4c17bd1f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# I'm defining my target column y and predictor columns X\n",
    "y = df_class['genre']\n",
    "X = df_class.drop(columns='genre')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "id": "a8d025de",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,random_state=10)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9337c029",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Encoding the categorical data to numerical data and creating a pipeline"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "95b90189",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next, I am going to use a pipeline encode my data and run my first models to start predicting!\n",
    "I will create 2 seperate pipelines and use logistic regression in first one and random forest classifier in second one."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "id": "759ff08f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Validation score  0.463111516256457\n",
      "Accuracy: 0.4767330568342373\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Creating seperate lists for categorical and numerical columns\n",
    "cat_cols = ['key', 'mode','time_signature']\n",
    "num_cols = ['acousticness', 'danceability', 'duration_ms', 'energy', 'instrumentalness',\n",
    "            'liveness', 'loudness', 'speechiness', 'tempo', 'valence']\n",
    "\n",
    "# Defining the column transformer for one-hot encoding categorical columns\n",
    "preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(\n",
    "    transformers=[\n",
    "        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'), cat_cols),('num', StandardScaler(), num_cols)], remainder='passthrough')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Defining the pipeline with preprocessor and logistic regression classifier\n",
    "pipe = Pipeline([\n",
    "    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),\n",
    "    ('clf', LogisticRegression())\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fitting the pipeline on the training data\n",
    "pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Making predictions on the test data\n",
    "y_pred = pipe.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Evaluating the performance of the model on the test data\n",
    "print(\"Validation score \", cross_val_score(pipe,X_train,y_train).mean())\n",
    "print('Accuracy:', accuracy_score(y_pred,y_test))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "id": "cc029872",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Validation score  0.5458067456700091\n",
      "Accuracy: 0.549428011485347\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Defining the second pipeline with preprocessor and random forest classifier\n",
    "pipe = Pipeline([\n",
    "    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),\n",
    "    ('classifier', RandomForestClassifier())\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fitting the pipeline on the training data\n",
    "pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Using the fitted pipeline to make predictions on the test data\n",
    "y_pred = pipe.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Computing the validation and accuracy score on the test data\n",
    "score = pipe.score(X_test, y_test)\n",
    "print(\"Validation score \", cross_val_score(pipe,X_train,y_train).mean())\n",
    "print('Accuracy:', accuracy_score(y_pred,y_test))\n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "#### Initial model summary\n",
    "I tried to classify 13 genres and my models are not doing great, they are working on 47% and 54% accuracy respectively. I will try to reduce my target classses to create a better model. I can go with top 5 most broad and popular genres for my new data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "34fd6879",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## EDA & Predictor models with 5 target genres\n",
    "In this part, I will create 6 different pipelines with different classifiers to get the best validation score.\n",
    "Classifiers will be as following:\n",
    "-Logistic Regression\n",
    "-K Nearest Neighbors\n",
    "-Decision Tree\n",
    "-Gradient Boosting\n",
    "-Extreme Gradient Boosting(XG Boost)\n",
    "\n",
    "Along the way, I will use hyperparameter tuning to improve my accuracy scores. With the help of GridSearchCV I could try different hyperparameters to see which hyperparameters works best for my data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e3005a8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Let's focus on 5 genres this time"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "id": "18260b49",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Creating a new list for top 5 genres\n",
    "reducedgenres = ['Pop','Electronic','Hip-Hop','Rock','Classical']\n",
    "\n",
    "# Creating a filtered dataframe with 5 genres\n",
    "loc_cond = [(x in reducedgenres) for x in df.genre]\n",

  {

   "source": [
    "### Train-test split and modeling"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 34,
   "id": "5bd6680d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Performing a train test split and defining target and predictor columns.\n",
    "y_reduced = df_reduced['genre']\n",
    "X_reduced = df_reduced.drop(columns=['genre'])\n",
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_reduced,y_reduced,random_state=10,test_size=0.3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "eb74fefd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "I'm creating a preprocessor to encode the categorical columns to numerical columns. Also, I'm using standart scaling to make sure my predictors are in the same scale."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 35,
   "id": "f07086f5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Defining the categorical and numeric columns\n",
    "cat_cols = ['key', 'mode']\n",
    "num_cols = ['acousticness', 'danceability', 'duration_ms', 'energy', 'instrumentalness',\n",
    "            'liveness', 'loudness', 'speechiness', 'tempo', 'valence','popularity']\n",
    "\n",
    "# Defining the column transformer for one-hot encoding categorical columns\n",
    "preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(\n",
    "    transformers=[\n",
    "        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'), cat_cols),('scl',StandardScaler(),num_cols)\n",
    "    ], remainder='passthrough')\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "id": "16f00c4c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Checking to see if there is imbalance in targets\n",
    "\n",
    "target_counts = y_reduced.value_counts()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a bar plot of the target variable counts\n",
    "plt.bar(target_counts.index, target_counts.values)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Set the plot title and axis labels\n",
    "plt.title('Target Variable Counts')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Target Classes')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Count')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Display the plot\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d0b71a16",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Targets are balanced, this means that I don't need to use sampling methods."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "81dcb208",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 1st Model: Logistic Regression\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 40,
   "id": "35bc5918",
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": true
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Validation score:  0.7560870898497394\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Creating a pipeline that includes preprocessing and logistic regression\n",
    "pipe_log = Pipeline([('preprocessing',preprocessor),('logreg',LogisticRegression())])\n",
    "\n",

    "This project aimed to develop a song genre classifier using Spotify dataset. The project included an exploratory data analysis phase, followed by the creation of baseline models and more advanced models using pipelines and grid searches. The performance of these models was evaluated on a hold-out test set, and the best-performing model was identified for genre classification.\n",
    "\n",
    "After investigating the data, the 26 genres were filtered to 13 broad genres, and then reduced to the top 5 most popular genres. Six different pipelines were created with different classifiers, and hyperparameter tuning was used to improve the accuracy scores. The XG Boost model was identified as the best model for genre classification with an accuracy score of 0.774.\n",

    "The project also identified the best predictors for song genre classification as popularity, acousticness, loudness, speechiness, and danceability. Visualizations were created to understand the differences between genres according to these features.\n",
